{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_inkster_ver01/data/sn88063294/00340589075/1945082101/0642.xml":{"full_text":"How Bad Will Unemployment Be?\nThe Sotting Sun Drop* lower;\nCREDENTIALS FROM HIS EMPEROR\nI\n.wk~.\n1>\nM Eh r mg i\ni M WIU\nJr**\nH JjP j\nx, i\n'T \u00bbr.;t;v\nLt. Gen. Kawahe Takitshiro, vice chief\nof the Japanese imperial wtaff and head\nof the 16-man Jap surrender party, turn\ning stiffly as he presents credentials\n150,000 Idled\nBy Cutbacks,\nTotal Rising\nLong linrs-of the in front\nof all Michigan unemployment\ncompensation commission offices\ntoday brought home to Detroit\nthe full effect of the war produc\ntion stoppage which ha foil -wed\npeace.\nEdward L Cushman, director of\nthe War Manpower Commisiion.\nestimated that there were 150 o*.\njobless workers in Detroit toda>\nan increase of 75,000 Since the\nJap surrender was announced last\nTuesday.\nMUCC iffidals said r would be\nImpossible to process mere ti an\n10.000 applications in the Detroit\narea today. Those still in line at\nthe close of business w .11 h. given\nappointment slip* and their ap\nplication dated as of t-><ii\\, they\nstated.\nLM.OOO APPLK XNTS\nMUCC officials said they ex\npect n minimum load cf I,V),(h>o\napplicants for compensation with\nin the next two weeks although\nthis does not represent the full\nunemployment load Tin* load\nthey said has increased I\n18.000 in March to 66.000 in the\nweek ending Aug. 11\nLines thiee block* long were\nwaiting in front of all 15 MUCC\noffices in the Detroit area when\nthey were opened this'morning.\nAlthough there was no disorder\npolice were stationed to maintain\nthe lines.\nComplicating the problem was\na manpower shortage in the\nMUCC offices, now desperately\nIn need of 600 extra worker*. The\noffices now employ 1,100.\nNEED SIKt CLERKS\nThree hundred more clerks\nwith a high school diploma and\none year of business experience\nare sought. About. 300 bookkeep\ning machine and comptometer\noperators and check writers are\nneeded\nTo relieve this situation. MUCC\nand civil service officials wore\nmeeting today It is the hope of\nEugene P IXormer. executive\ndirector of the MUCC that the\ncivil service commission and ih\"\nsocial security board will waive\nsome requirements so that the\nworkers can he quickly heard.\nDormer said all MUCC em\nployes will go on a six-day week\nimmediately.\nMUCC heads said it requires\n25 minutes to process each appli\ncant and 10 days to complete the\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 4)\nSlam Tolls 1 S.\nWar W as Error\nWASHINGTON. Aug. 20 (UP)\n-~The United States has accepted\nthe assurances of Thailand (Siam)\nthat her declaration of war\nagainst this country was dictated\nby the Japanese and \"contrary to\nthe will of the Thai people.\u2019\u2019\nit ft Army Signal C rp\u00bb Photo H\u00bb<lU*4 from Manila. Distributed by Intcmttloiitl Bound Pfcotoa\n(See Other Picture in Pictorial Review.)\nHow Bad Will Unemployment Be?\nBack to Work\nlino By Oct. 1\nBv SILER FREEMAN\n'THE automobile industry today is in a \u201cmarvelous\nA state of confusion.\u201d\nIt knows it is going some place but it doesn\u2019t\nknow how soon.\nBut out of this state of confusion, a few clear\ncut facts emerge:\n1 \u2014Unemployment will be severe but of short dura\ntion. Employment probably will pick up around\nOct. 1, and show gradual improvement for the rest\nof the year.\nO\u2014Most materials will be plentiful when cancella\ntions are fully unleashed by the official procla\nmation of V-J Day.\nO\u2014A postwar market of 15,000,000 cars awaits and\nwill spearhead the greatest era of prosperity the\nindustry has ever known.\n\nMUCH of the confusion that besets the auto industry\ntodav can be blamed directly on the Japs.\nTheir stalling tactics, delaying official V-J Day, have\nmade the military sen ices cautious in approving; whole\nsale cancellations of war goods.\nWhile many war orders have been cut off. there have been\nno blanket cancellations.\nSome contracts, halted once, have been reinstated, such as\nthe Ford tank engine.\nBut this will clear up fast, according.to Carstcn Tiedeman,\nWPB regional director.\nConfidential order s are going out to the contractors\nwhich will indicate to what items are to be cut off en\ntirely and what are to be retained. This action will\naid the manufacturers materially, enabling them to\nplan their production lines better.\n\nWHEN final cancellations are made after V-J Day, the ranks\nof the jobless here are expected to reach 250,000 to 300.000.\nMuch of the work force, mainly males, will be put on plant\nclearances and reconversion. Many others will find places in\nthe expansion plans of the auto makers, on new construction.\nThe most pessimistic observers do not expect this temporary\nsituation to last beyond October.\nGeorge Romney, head of the Automobile Manufac\nturers\u2019 Association, predicts that by Oct. 1 the upswing\nwill start.\nWhile auto manufacturing is viewed mainly as an assembly\noperation. 90 per cent of the workers are employed on parts. So\nthe pickup in employment, will be gradual but steady as the\nindustry makes parts to get geared to volume production.\n\nTHE materials situation appears brighter every day. The\naction of WPB in dropping the Controlled Materials Plan\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 1)\nDick Powell and Bride\nHoneymoon on Yacht\nHOLLYWOOD. Aug 20 (INS)\nDick Powell, aboard his yacht\nthat had been tied up since Pearl\nHarbor as a result of wartime\n\\son a wedding\ncruise today with his bride of a\nday, June Ally son.\nfrom Iflirnhitn to Lt. Orn. .Sutherland,\nchief of staff to Gen. .Mar Arthur at\nGeneral Headquarter*, Manila. The Jap\nparty Is now en route back to Tokyo.\nSoon# Accused\nOf Opal With Reds\nWASHINGTON. Aug. 20 (INS)\nI \u2014Dr. James S. Shinn, director\ngeneral of the Korean-American\ncouncil, charged today that\nChinese foreign minister T. V.\nSrong was striving to use Korea\nas \"a pawn to turn over to the\n-Soviet Union the fate of 30,000.000\nI Koreans.\"\nBIG YANK ARMY\nTO ENTER TOKYO\nWITHIN 10 DAYS\nBandits Flee\nBob-Lo With\nSIO,OOO Loot\nUsing a speedboat In pirate\nfa*kiion, four armed bandits early\ntoday invaded Bo Lo Island in the\nlower Detroit river and took the\nweek-end receipts of SIO,OOO after\nthe night watchman and\ncowing two other employes.\nBob l*o company officials said\nthe four river marauders landed\non the north end of the island at\n2 am. Reaching their craft, the\nquartet broke a section of the\nfence separating the amusement\ncenter from the water\u2019s edge apd\nslunk through the darkness to\nenter the main administration\nbuilding.\nTRAP WATCHMAN\nNight watchman Fred Nestor\nwas just leaving the building.\n\"One ofUhr bandits slugged\nNester with a club,\" Boh Lo\nofficials said, \"and knocked him\nunconscious.\n\u201cThen the four rounded up\ntwo cafeteria employes and\nwent into the room where the\nthree steel safes are kept. Thev\nsmashed the safes with heavy\nsledge hammers.\"\nAfter breaking the safe, the\nofficial said, the four forced cafe\nteria employe John J. McAtte. 75.\nand another employe, to hold\nlarge cloth sacks into which the\nloot was poured.\nTOOK THEIR TIME\nWhen the last of the money was\ntaken from the safes, each man\nshouldered one of the heavy bags\nof plunder and made their way\nback to their boat.\nThe bandits were on the island\nfrom 2 a. m. until 4 a. m., the\nofficial said.\nMcAtte and Nestor, the latter\nwho was just regaining conscious\nness. heard the boat start and\nspeed away.\nBecause Boh-Lo is a Canadian\nowned island. Canadian provincial\npolice were called in on the case.\nDetroit police also were called in\nbecause it is not known whether\nthe bandits came from the Amer\nican or Canadian side.\nUNABLE TO DESCRIBE\nNeither Nestor or McAtte was\nable to give police a clear descrip\ntion of the four men.\n\"I wax too frightened.\" Mc-\nAtte said, \"that the only thing\nI thought about wax doing what\nI wax told and hoping they\nwould leave without harming\nanyone elxe.\"\nTHE WEATHER\nhoi m.r TrMri a sTt arx\n12 mid xx S m *7 Ida m XS\nlam XX X\u00bbm X 2 lit n 73\n2\u00abm xx 7 m xo 13 no\u00abn 77\n.1 1 m XX ft m xx 1 p m 83\n4 a m 64 9am x 3\nThe tun will tet at 24 r m today\nand rla* tomorrow at x ax a m\nm* moon will rt\u00bb* at s M p m today\nand art tomorrow at 4 17 a m.\n\u2022*W\u00abr*n'! th\u00bb\nJaps going\nto dictate\nsurrender terms\nin the\nWhite House?\u2019*\nFORECAST:\nFair and mild 1\ntonight. Increas\ning cloudiness\ntomorrow with\nthundershowers\nby late afternoon or night.\nToday*! pone* count It 114,\nE S\nOnly Detroit Newspaper Carrying Both International News Service and United Preas\nC Detroit 31, Mich., Tuesday, Aug. 21,1945\n\u00ab\u00bbrn vs 4a,\nho m\n-Japan\nYields\nTo Reds\nLONDON, Aug. 20. (UP)\n.The 11-day Russo-Japanese war\nended today with the capitulation\nof the Kwantung army that\nlaunched Japan's bid for Asiatic\nconquest 14 years ago. Soviet\narmies occupied Manchuria's four\nmajor cities and began disarming\nsome 750.000 enemy troops.\nMoscow's formal victory procla\nmation was being withheld early\ntoday, apparently awaiting the\ncomplete disarmament of the re\nmaining Japanese in Manchuria.\nKorea and Sakhalin island.\nRESISTANCE HAS ENDED\nBut Japanese resistance had\nended almost everywhere and up\nward of 1.000.000 Soviet troops\nwere moving unopposed into key\nports and communications centers.\nRussian paratroops and air\nborne infantrymen wrote off the\nbattle of Manchuria late yester\nday with a series of surprise\nlandings on Mukden. Harbin.\nKirin and Hsinking. kingpins of\nthe Japanese defensive system in\nthe puppet state.\nTokyo's Domei news agency\nsaid Soviet military envoys fol\nlowed the paratroops into Hsin\nking. headquarters of the Kwan\ntung army, and that surrender\nnegotiations were begun immedi\nately.\nSurrender in China\nCHUNGKING. Aug.'2o (INS)\nGen Ho Ying-Chin, commander of\nChina's field forces, left Chung\nking today for Chihkiang in west\nern Hunan Province to accept the\nJapanese surrender on behalf of\nGeneralissimo Chiang Kai-shek.\nThe Japanese commander. Gen.\nYusuji Okamura wirelessed Chiang\nKai-shek yesterday that he had\naccepted the Chinese surrender\nultimatum and would send surren\ndef envoys to Chihkiang Monday.\nSingapore Finally\nLearns Surrender\nLONDON, Aug. 20 (INS)\u2014The\nNew Delhi radio reported today\nthat the Jap-controlled transmit\nter at Singapore, occupied British\nnaval base, told its listeners for\nihe first time today that Japan\nhad surrendered to the Allies.\nBougainville Yielding\nSA N FRANCISCO, Aug 20\n(INS) Radio Melhnurne said to\nday that the Japanese commander\nof isolated units on Bougainville\nwill he picked up by an Australian\ncorvette today to arrange for for-,\nmal surrender.\n7 Chetniks Executed\nLONDON. Aug. 20 (UP)\u2014Seven\nmembers of Draga Mihailovitch\u2019s\ncentral committee were executed\nrecently in Belgrade, dispatches\nfrom Yugoslavia said today.\nMeal Outlook Better:\nPoint Luts Exported\nWASHINGTON. Aug 20 (UP)\n\u2014The OPA plans to lower the\npoint values of many cuts of\nmeat in September, it w-as under\nstood today\nEnd of moat and possibly butter\nrationing is expected to follow\nlater in the fail unless unforeseen\n3 Arrested\nIn Windsor's\n3 Murders\nFear gripped Windsor residents\ntoday as dominion, provincial and\ncity police continued a searph for\nhomicidal maniacs w-ho have\nslashed two men to death and\nclubbed another to death since\nAug. 8.\nj Rewards totaling 53.000 have\nbeen posted for the slayers, while\nleaves have been canceled and 12-\nhour shifts set up for all police in\nthe jittery, rumor-ridden city.\nDETROIT POLICE HELP\nMeanwhile, the Detroit Police\nDepartment assigned a detective\nteam to investigate undisclosed\nleads on this side of the river.\nNeither Detective Lt. Harry\nO\u2019Brien nor Sgt. Gene Kenney\nwould discuss the nature of the\nDetroit clues, however.\nFrank Sciegliski, killed Aug. 8,\nand Sgt. Hugh Blackwood Price,\nkilled early Saturday, were\nstabbed to death. William Davies,\na garage night watchman, died\nfrom skull fractures inflicted with\na hamrrier last Thursday.\nPolice are detaining three un\nidentified suspects in the slaying.\nThey admitted, however, that they\nwere without substantial clues\nand could only speculate about\nmotives in the slayings.\nDISCOUNT WALL MESSAGE\nPolice were inclined to discount\nthe imporiapce of a scrawled\npencilled message on a wall at the\nWindsor end of the Detroit-\nWmdsor tunnel.\nSigned by \"Slasher Evans,\" the\nmessage declared \"I\u2019ll strike again.\nNext time\u2014a girl.\"\nThe writer identified himself as\nan American soldier discharged\ndishonorably because \"I killed a\nGerman in a prison camp.\"\nWindsor police sent a text of\nthe message to the FBI in Wash\nington.\nPublic parks and other places\nof comparative seclusion within\nthe city are under constant patrol\nby alerted police who tear the\nkiller may strike again.\nSIMILAR KILLINGS\nPolice think at least two of the\nthree were slam by the same per\nson. Price s body was found about\n150 yards from the scene of the\nSciegliski murder on Sandwich\nstreet near the Detroit River.\nTheir stab wounds were inflicted\nsimilarly.\nRobbery might have been Ihe\nmotive in the Davies slaving. De\ntective Inspector Duncan Mac Nab\nsaid.\nPolice headquarters have been\nflooded With calls from distraut\nresidents. All\u2019reports are being\ncarefully sifted for clues, Mac Nab\nsaid.\nsupply complications arise.\nTrie outlook for the civilian\nmeat situation became brighter\nover the week-end when Secre\ntary of Agriculture Anderson\nannounced the suspension of set\naside orders on beef, veal and\n\u2022hams.\n5 Cents\nPeace Envoys\nFlying Home\nMANILA, Aug. 20 (INS) \u2014The final curtain\nwill fall on history\u2019s bloodiest war within 10 days\nwith the signing of Japan\u2019s formal surrender, Gen.\nMacArthur announced today after Emepor Hiro*\nhito\u2019s peace messengers had left Manila to return\nto Tokyo.\nThe Allied supreme commander, indicating that the\nepochal capitulation ceremony will be held on Japanese\nhome territory itself\u2014perhaps in Tokyo\u2014declared that he\nand his conquering legions will land in vanquished Nippon\nwithin 10 days, \u201csubject to weather that will permit land\nings,\u201d\nWainwright\nCoup Assailed\nMANILA, Aug. 20 (INS)\u2014\nJapan protested today against the\nrescue of Lt. Gen. Jonathan M.\nWainwright and other prisoners\non the Asiatic continent, but this\nwas not exacted to interfere with\nany possible further operations of\nthis sort.\nThe Japanese offered the flimsy\nargument that such rescues, car\nried out ny parachutists, are\n\"likely to hamper\u201d the complete\n\"cessation of hostilities.\"\nLIBERATE PRISONERS\nIt was apparent, however, with\nannouncement of the liberation of\nGen. Wainwright that the Allies\nhad no intention of allowing pris\noners of war to remain in Jap\nhands during lengthy pre-surren\nder negotiations.\nThe widespread extent of the\nAllied rescue operations was ac\nknowledged by the Japs who con\nfirmed an Allied announcement\nthat parachutists had landed last\nThursday at camps near Mukdojx.\nin Manchuria. Keiho in Korea, and\nHong Kong.\nWainwright, highest ranking\nAllied prisoner of the Japanese,\nwas expected to' land at Chung\nking airdrome within the next 48-\nhours.\nTIME FOR CEREMONIES\nHis friends hoped that the man\nthey had affectionately called\n\"Skinny,\" who was forced Into un\nconditional surrender on Corregi\ndor May 6. 1942, would reach\nManila in time to participate in\nthe Japanese surrender cere\nmonies.\nLt. Gen. Albert C\ncommander of United States\nforces in China, said that six-man\nAmerican army parachute teams\nconsisting of doctors and signal\nmen had parachuted into the\nMukden area on Aug. 16\nWainwright was liberated from\na ramp at Sian, 100 miles north\neast of Mukden.\nMessages radioed hack said the\nprisoners' overall condition was\n\"much better than expected.\"\nIn the Times TODAY\nr\u00bb\u00bbx\nfjtirrn S\nPrater t\nRa4to Prorrama It\nRation hut t\u00bb\nRiplr. It\nRanrop\nft or let r t\nsport, 14. If\nMate, ftrreen 20\nVrlerana' fter.lr*\nWant Ma lt 17\nWin-hell\nWi.hlnc Well It\nW bat the\nlaiart t\nWafttn Pft\u00ab\u00ab t\nrace\nSutler Nrftlth\nI\u00bb<*b Hop*\n\u201cBait' Baxr\nCa\u00abualll*\u00ab 10\nomir* It. 1*\nrr\u00bbu\u00bb<(4 filil* 41\nDlv>n\nDurtlnr\nMltsrul x.r* t\nFralarr\nFlntn, Ul IO\nHttlo\u2018l art eon lt\nKm m Koii io\nHnro.inp* I\nMallon\nWar* Haworth\nMftvM frocratM I\nRED\nLINE\n\u201cI shall soon proceed to\nJapan.\u201d the five-star general\nproclaimed, \u201cwith accompany\ning force* composed of air,\nground and naval element*.\nHe said that the Japanese sur\nrender delegates, in two action\npacked sessions in Manila\u2019s war\nbatter ed city hall, had provided\n\"all the information required\" for\nNippon\u2019s imminent occupation\nthe triumphant end of the long\nroad back from earl Harbor.\nSIGNING Dl E IN 10 DATS\nThe stalwart MacArthur, who\nrose out of the tragedy of Bataan\nto lead his armies to avenging\nvictory, said he anticipates tha\nsigning and execution of the final,\nformal instrument of Japan's cap\nitulation within 10 days.\n\"It is my earnest hope that,\npending the formal accomplish\nment of the Instrument of sur\nrender, armistice conditions may\nprevail on every front and\nbloodless surrender may bo\neffectuated,\u201d he said.\nMacArthur indicated airborne\ntroops will spearhead the million\nman army of occupation by land\ning on Tokyo airfields.\nGreat amphibious forces are\naboard ships, some of which are\nbelieved steaming toward Japan's\nshores.\nWILL SMOTHER RESISTANCE\nMacArthur asserted his mighty\nforces would land with such speed\nand in such strength that any\nJap hot-head groups would be\ni powerless to resist.\nAdm. Halsey\u2019s tremendous Third\nFleet is expected to steam in close\nto Japan\u2019s shores to give occupa\ntion troop* the same protection a\nlighting invasion force would\nreceive.\nMacArthur, who had no per\u00bb\nsonal contact with the Jap dele\ngates in the Manila talks, revealed\nthe enemy's complete submission\nto his demands shortly after Hiro\nhito's 16-man delegation left fop\nTokyo hearing a blueprint for tha\napproaching occupation.\n21 HOt'RS IN MANILA\nThe Jap party, headed by Lt.\nGen. Torashiro Kawabe, took off\nfrom Nichols Field in an American\nC-54 transport plane at 3:03 p. m.\n<2 03 a. m. EWTi. after a stay of\nlittle more than 21 hours in tbn\nPhilippine capital.\nMacArthur advised Tokyo In a\nradiogram that the Jap envoy*\nprobably would land at Kisanuu\nairdrome, southeast of the\nJapanese capital tonight.\nOn Ie Island, the Jap dele\ngation was due to transfer from\nthe C-JS4 transport to two white\npainted Jananese planes which\nwill take them the rest of the\nwav to Tokyo.\nMacArthur told Tokyo that\n(Continued on Page 2, CoL","height":"27864","width":"21387"}}
